<h2 id="chart">On the chart itself</h2>
<p class="intro">These print as literal legend or key text on a rendered chart.</p>

<p class="term">Cartouche</p>
<p class="def">The decorative title panel on an antique-style chart.</p>

<p class="term">Fathom</p>
<p class="def">A unit of water depth equal to six feet (about 1.8 meters),
the traditional unit for nautical soundings. Vellum's depth readings are
labeled in fathoms.</p>

<p class="term">Hypsometric tint</p>
<p class="def">Shading land by elevation band, the coloring scheme used on
the topographic style.</p>

<p class="term">Isohyet</p>
<p class="def">A line connecting points of equal rainfall, the contour lines
on the Rainfall plate.</p>

<p class="term">Isotherm</p>
<p class="def">A line connecting points of equal temperature, the contour
lines on the Temperature plate.</p>

<p class="term">Realm seat</p>
<p class="def">A settlement that serves as a realm's seat of power: the
capital, or one of its smaller provincial seats.</p>

<p class="term">Recto</p>
<p class="def">The front of a chart: the side the map is drawn on. Turn the
sheet over in the Explorer to find its verso.</p>

<p class="term">Rhumb line</p>
<p class="def">A straight line of constant compass bearing, radiating from
the compass rose in the old navigator's style.</p>

<p class="term">Rock awash</p>
<p class="def">A nautical chart mark for a rock exposed or barely covered at
the surface, a hazard to ships.</p>

<p class="term">Shoal / danger line</p>
<p class="def">A tinted shallow-water zone on nautical charts, bounded by a
dashed line marking the hazardous edge.</p>

<p class="term">Sounding</p>
<p class="def">A numbered depth reading, in fathoms, scattered over open
water on nautical charts.</p>

<p class="term">Surveyor's glass</p>
<p class="def">The hand lens kept on the chart table, and the Explorer's
magnifier named for it. Lean closer over an antique chart and the surveyor
redrafts the window under the glass as a finer regional survey, its coastline
inked in and its newly placed names drying by tier; stand back and the full
sheet returns.</p>

<p class="term">Verso</p>
<p class="def">The back of a chart. Real charts were folded into pilot books
and docketed on the reverse, so Vellum's verso carries a docket line, the
surveyor's attribution, and a survey-office stamp. Turn the sheet in the
Explorer to read it.</p>

<h2 id="climate">Weather &amp; climate</h2>

<p class="term">Biome</p>
<p class="def">A category of plant and animal life shaped by climate.
Tundra, taiga, steppe, savanna, and forest all appear across Vellum's
worlds.</p>

<p class="term">Orographic</p>
<p class="def">Having to do with how mountains shape weather, especially by
wringing rain out of wind forced upward: orographic lift on the wet side,
a rain shadow on the dry one.</p>

<p class="term">Prevailing wind</p>
<p class="def">A world's dominant wind direction, drawn as arrows on
nautical charts.</p>

<p class="term">Windward / leeward</p>
<p class="def">The side of high ground facing into the wind, which catches
the rain, versus the sheltered side, which stays dry.</p>

<h2 id="heraldry">Heraldry (coats of arms)</h2>

<p class="term">Blazon</p>
<p class="def">To formally describe or display a coat of arms.</p>

<p class="term">Charge</p>
<p class="def">A symbol or figure placed on a shield.</p>

<p class="term">Ordinary</p>
<p class="def">A simple geometric band across a shield: a cross, chevron,
bend, fess, or pale.</p>

<p class="term">Rule of tincture</p>
<p class="def">The heraldic law that color can't sit on color, nor metal on
metal, so a shield always reads clearly at a glance. Every coat of arms
Vellum draws obeys it.</p>

<p class="term">Tincture</p>
<p class="def">The limited heraldic palette: two metals (gold, <em>or</em>;
silver, <em>argent</em>) and five colors (red, <em>gules</em>; blue,
<em>azure</em>; black, <em>sable</em>; green, <em>vert</em>; purple,
<em>purpure</em>).</p>

<h2 id="geography">Geography &amp; place</h2>

<p class="term">Archipelago</p>
<p class="def">A scattered group of islands, one of Vellum's four map
types.</p>

<p class="term">Atelier</p>
<p class="def">An artist's workshop. Vellum calls itself "an atelier of
imaginary cartography" in its own footer.</p>

<p class="term">Confluence</p>
<p class="def">The point where two rivers meet.</p>

<p class="term">Estuary</p>
<p class="def">The widening mouth of a river where it meets the sea.</p>

<p class="term">Gazetteer</p>
<p class="def">A directory of place names. Vellum's gazetteer lists every
town on the map, grouped by realm, with a line or two of travelers'
notes.</p>

<p class="term">Hinterland</p>
<p class="def">The inland territory a city depends on, especially a
city-state's supporting countryside.</p>

<p class="term">Vellum</p>
<p class="def">Prepared animal skin used as a writing and drawing surface
for real medieval maps and manuscripts, the material this whole project
takes its name from.</p>

<p class="term">Watershed</p>
<p class="def">The boundary between two river drainage systems. Vellum's
realm borders prefer to follow these.</p>

<h2 id="names">Words on your own map</h2>
<p class="intro">Each of Vellum's six invented cultures borrows its realm
and place-name vocabulary from a real language or region that matches its
sound. Here's what those words mean where they come from, grouped by the
culture that uses them.</p>

<h3>Norden, the hard northern tongue</h3>

<p class="term">Fell</p>
<p class="def">A mountain or stretch of high, barren moorland, a word used
in Northern England and Scandinavia.</p>

<p class="term">Jarldom</p>
<p class="def">The territory or rank of a jarl, an Old Norse nobleman
roughly equal to an earl.</p>

<p class="term">March</p>
<p class="def">A borderland or frontier territory, the root of "the Welsh
Marches" and "margrave."</p>

<h3>Oromi, the island tongue</h3>

<p class="term">Atoll</p>
<p class="def">A ring-shaped coral reef, island, or islet chain enclosing a
lagoon.</p>

<p class="term">Chiefdom</p>
<p class="def">A hierarchical society under a paramount chief, more
organized than a tribe, less centralized than a state. Historically the
term used for pre-contact Hawaiian and other Pacific island societies.</p>

<h3>Sylvan, the woodland tongue</h3>

<p class="term">Downs</p>
<p class="def">Open, grassy chalk upland, like England's South Downs.</p>

<p class="term">Mere</p>
<p class="def">An old word for a lake or shallow pond.</p>

<p class="term">Tor</p>
<p class="def">A rocky hilltop or craggy outcrop.</p>

<p class="term">Vale</p>
<p class="def">An archaic word for valley.</p>

<p class="term">Wold</p>
<p class="def">Open, rolling, treeless upland, like England's Yorkshire
Wolds or the Cotswolds.</p>

<h3>Thalassic &amp; Draket, the seafaring and mountain-clan tongues</h3>

<p class="term">Dominion</p>
<p class="def">A territory under a ruler's control. Historically also the
term for self-governing territories of the British Empire.</p>

<h3>Veshari, the desert tongue</h3>

<p class="term">Sultanate</p>
<p class="def">The territory or reign of a sultan, a Muslim sovereign.</p>

<p class="term">Wadi</p>
<p class="def">A valley or channel that runs dry except in the rainy
season, in North Africa and the Middle East.</p>
